        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 470,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-11T03:14:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "SkTArray currently guarantees that if you call `reserve_back(lots)`, you can push_back and pop_back as much as you want and it will never shrink until count \u003e lots (at which point it goes back to the typical shrink/grow behavior). Is this a guarantee that we care about? We have a test for this behavior in `test_array_reserve`. If we don\u0027t care about this, removing fReserved works fine. My gut feeling is that it\u0027s worth one bit to preserve the current behavior, but I don\u0027t have a strong feeling either way.\n\nhttp://review.skia.org/333876",
      "parentUuid": "21407fec_594b0518",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 470,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 470,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "bd25c98593712f1d51dd5037d8f13018bf87db2d",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "cc615391_66c212fc",
        "filename": "include/private/SkTArray.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 470,
      "author": {
        "id": 5045
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-11T14:01:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "333876 is not what I was suggesting.  My thinking when I said \"but I kind of think you don\u0027t need to track that bit if you just make growing ops only check to grow up, shrinking ops only check to shrink down,\" was that we could have push_back() guarantee to only grow or stay the same size, never shrink.  So reserve-push-push-push would be natively safe without tracking this fReserved bit.  I hadn\u0027t considered reserve-push-pop-push-pop.\n\nLet\u0027s forget the whole idea... after sleeping on it, I don\u0027t want to keep burning effort on SkTArray unless we\u0027re trying to delete it.",
      "parentUuid": "014f86cd_daae5c24",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 470,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 470,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "bd25c98593712f1d51dd5037d8f13018bf87db2d",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": false,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "5105bd3b_8f40b6a7",
        "filename": "include/private/SkTArray.h",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 470,
      "author": {
        "id": 11059
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-11-11T15:58:50Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "+1 to abandoning 333876, I don\u0027t think it\u0027s worth it. It removes a slightly-useful feature and provides very little in return.\n\nWhen I was new on the team I was on team \"delete SkTArray\" but honestly I haven\u0027t yet seen a replacement class that I would consider as a worthy successor. Using SkSTArray in SkSL has been quite beneficial for performance, and the ability to commingle SkTArray and SkSTArray is super powerful and I wouldn\u0027t want to sacrifice it. vector\u003cT\u003e doesn\u0027t have an SkSTArray equivalent at all; even if you implemented your own allocator to do something similar, that alters the type to vector\u003cT, MyAlloc\u003cT\u003e\u003e, so it\u0027s not transparently substitutable with vector\u003cT\u003e\u0026 in code (unless you template everything?). absl::InlinedVector\u003cT\u003e is great, but it doesn\u0027t even try to play nice with vector\u003cT\u003e\u0026.",
      "parentUuid": "cc615391_66c212fc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 470,
        "startChar": 7,
        "endLine": 470,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "bd25c98593712f1d51dd5037d8f13018bf87db2d",
